      story: {
        1: "Long ago, there lived a king who had many beautiful daughters. But the youngest was so lovely that the sun himself wondered at her beauty every time that he saw her.<br/>Near the king's castle was a large, dark forest. In this forest stood an old lime tree, right beside a spring.<br/>One day the king's youngest daughter came to this tree and sat down in the shade to rest. After a while she began to toss up her golden ball and catch it as it fell.<br/>At last, she failed to catch it. The ball fell on the ground and rolled into the spring. Splash! It went out of sight. The little princess began to sob and weep.",
        2: "Suddenly a voice called out, “O king's daughter, why are you weeping? Tell me your trouble and I may help you.”<br/>She looked toward the spot from where came the voice. There he was, a frog with his head stretched out of the water.<br/>“Was it you, old frog, that spoke?” she asked. “You cannot help me. I am weeping because I have lost my golden ball which rolled into the spring.”<br/>“Then weep no more,” said the frog. “I can get it out. But what will you give me if I bring back your toy?”<br/>“Oh, anything that you like, dear frog,” said the princess. “Would you like to have my silk dress, or perhaps my necklace of pearls, or even my golden crown? I like my golden ball best of all.”<br/>“Dresses and pearls and golden crowns are nothing to me,” said the frog. “I wish to be your friend and playmate. I wish to sit at your table, to eat the same food as you, to drink the same drink as you, and to live in your garden. If you will promise me these things, I will bring back your golden ball.”<br/>“Oh, yes,” she said, thinking only of her pretty toy. “I promise to give you whatever you wish for.”",
        3: "Hearing the princess’s promise, down dived the frog. Splash! <br/>Soon he came up with the golden ball in his mouth. He rolled it on the grass and the king's daughter picked it up, with a loud cry of joy. Then she ran home as fast as her feet could go.<br/>“Wait, wait!”, cried the frog. “Wait, I cannot hop as fast as you can run.”<br/>But the king's daughter did not stop to listen to his croak. She went home and forgot all about him.",
        4: "The next day, the king, the queen, and their daughters were sitting together at the table. The little princess was eating from her golden plate and drinking from her golden cup.<br/>All at once something came...splish-splash...splish-splash...up the marble stairs.<br/>Then there was a knock at the door and a voice cried,<br/>“Youngest daughter of the king, open the door and let me in.”",
        5: "The little princess went to see who was there. She was completely frightened when she saw the frog that had brought back her ball. She shut the door in his face and ran back to the table.<br/>“My child, why do you look so frightened?” asked the king. “Did you find a great giant at the door?”<br/>“Oh, no, father,” she said, “it is no giant, but an ugly old frog.”<br/>“A frog! And what does he want with you?” asked the king.<br/>“Listen, father, and I will tell you all about it,” said the little princess, in tears. “Yesterday, I was playing beside the spring and my golden ball fell into the water. I cried bitterly, and then this frog came and fetched it for me. But he made me promise that he might sit at the table with me and eat the same food as me and drink the same drink as me and sleep in my garden. But oh, father, I did not think of what I promised. I never dreamed the frog could get out of the water and come here. But now he is at the door.”",
        6: "Just then came a second knock.<br/>“King's daughter, king's daughter! Keep your word and open to me.”<br/>“My daughter,” said the king, “as you have made a promise, you must keep it. Go and let the frog in.”<br/>The king's daughter went slowly and sadly to open the door. The frog hopped in and went to her chair.<br/>“Take me up beside you,” he cried.<br/>She waited so long to do this that her father said, “My daughter, what you have promised, that you must do.”",
        7: "So she took the frog up and he jumped upon the table. “Please let me have a plate and eat the same food as you. I would love it if we ate together,” he said.<br/>The princess did so, but everyone could see how much she disliked it. “Now,” said the frog, “please give me a golden cup like yours and let me have the same drink as you.”<br/>This is also, what the little princess had to do.<br/>At last, the frog said: “I have both eaten and drank all that I wish. Now I am tired. Carry me outside into your garden and put me in a shady spot, so that I may sleep out there as you promised.”",
        8: "At these words, the princess began to weep. She was afraid to touch the frog, and she did not wish him to sleep in her garden.<br/>But her tears only made her father angry.<br/>“He helped you when you were in trouble, little princess,” he said. “Now you must keep your promise to him.”",
        9: "The princess took the frog in two fingers and carried him to her garden. She put him down in one corner.<br/>But he hopped from the corner and said, “I am tired. Put me in a shady spot in your garden or I will tell your father.”<br/>This made the princess angry. She told him, “Do be quiet, you ugly frog.”",
        10: "Then tears of shame came into her eyes at her bad temper and her broken promise. And lo and behold! There stood, instead of a frog, a young man, richly dressed.<br/>“Do not weep, little princess,” he said. “Yours was a promise hard to keep. But by keeping your promise, you have freed me from a witch's spell.<br/>Years ago she changed me from a prince into a frog. And a frog I would stay, she said, until I could find a princess who would let me sit beside her at the table and eat the same food as her and drink the same drink as her and even put me to sleep in her garden. I thought that would never happen. But it did and now, I am free. You freed me from the witch’s spell. Now I shall be king and I wish you to be my queen.”",
        11: "The next morning, a splendid coach drawn by eight white horses came to take the young king home to his mighty kingdom. Behind the coach stood the faithful Henry. He had been the servant of the young prince. When his master had changed into a frog, Henry grieved so much that he had to bind three iron bands around his heart to keep it from breaking.",
        12: "And as the sun set, away went the coach with the young king and his beautiful bride. Behind rode the faithful Henry. They had not gone far when the young king heard a loud crack, as if something had broken.<br/>He cried out, “Henry, is that the coach breaking?”<br/>“No, my king,” said the faithful Henry. “It is only one of the iron bands around my heart. I put them there to keep it from breaking with grief when you were changed into a frog. The band breaks now because my heart is full of joy at seeing you free.”<br/>Twice more came the same sound. Then all three of the bands were broken, and Henry’s heart, like his master, was at last free and happy."
      },
